## üîπ 1. Object Cloning
Objects are reference types. Assigning one object to another does not create a copy.
```javascript
const original = { a: 1, b: 2 };
const copy = original;
copy.a = 99;
console.log(original.a); // 99 (both change)
```

## üîπ 2. Using Spread to Clone
Spread syntax creates a shallow copy.
```javascript
const original = { a: 1, b: 2 };
const copy = { ...original };
copy.a = 99;
console.log(original.a); // 1 (original unchanged)
```

